---
import HebrewLayout from '../../layouts/HebrewLayout.astro';

const allLetters = [
  { num: 1,  char: 'א', name: 'Aleph',  done: true  },
  { num: 2,  char: 'ב', name: 'Bet',    done: false },
  { num: 3,  char: 'ג', name: 'Gimel',  done: false },
  { num: 4,  char: 'ד', name: 'Dalet',  done: false },
  { num: 5,  char: 'ה', name: 'He',     done: false },
  { num: 6,  char: 'ו', name: 'Vav',    done: false },
  { num: 7,  char: 'ז', name: 'Zayin',  done: false },
  { num: 8,  char: 'ח', name: 'Chet',   done: false },
  { num: 9,  char: 'ט', name: 'Tet',    done: false },
  { num: 10, char: 'י', name: 'Yod',    done: false },
  { num: 11, char: 'כ', name: 'Kaf',    done: false },
  { num: 12, char: 'ל', name: 'Lamed',  done: false },
  { num: 13, char: 'מ', name: 'Mem',    done: true  },
  { num: 14, char: 'נ', name: 'Nun',    done: false },
  { num: 15, char: 'ס', name: 'Samech', done: false },
  { num: 16, char: 'ע', name: 'Ayin',   done: false },
  { num: 17, char: 'פ', name: 'Pe',     done: false },
  { num: 18, char: 'צ', name: 'Tsade',  done: false },
  { num: 19, char: 'ק', name: 'Qof',    done: false },
  { num: 20, char: 'ר', name: 'Resh',   done: false },
  { num: 21, char: 'ש', name: 'Shin',   done: false },
  { num: 22, char: 'ת', name: 'Tav',    done: true  },
];
---

<HebrewLayout
  title="Yahushua in Every Letter — Hebrew — Nazaryah"
  description="How Yahushua the Messiah embodies and fulfills every one of the 22 Hebrew letters — from Aleph to Taw."
>
  <!-- ── HERO ── -->
  <section class="hl-hero">
    <a href="/hebrew" class="hl-back">&#8592; Back to Hebrew</a>
    <p class="hl-label">&#8213; A Scripture Study &#8213;</p>
    <h1 class="hl-title">Yahushua in Every Letter</h1>
    <span class="heb-display">א &nbsp; מ &nbsp; ת</span>
    <p class="hl-sub">
      The Hebrew aleph-bet is not merely an alphabet. Each letter carries a concept rooted in its ancient form. When those concepts are held against the life and mission of Yahushua the Messiah — and tested against Scripture that is specifically about the Son — the letters become a testimony written before He arrived.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- ── LETTER OVERVIEW GRID (5-wide) ── -->
  <section class="hl-section">
    <h2 class="hl-section-title hl-center">The Twenty-Two Letters</h2>
    <p class="hl-section-sub hl-center">Three studies published. Nineteen in progress.</p>
    <div class="letter-grid">
      {allLetters.map((l) => (
        l.done ? (
          <a href={`#${l.name.toLowerCase()}`} class="letter-tile tile-done">
            <span class="tile-char">{l.char}</span>
            <span class="tile-name">{l.name}</span>
            <span class="tile-num">{l.num} of 22</span>
            <span class="tile-badge">Published</span>
          </a>
        ) : (
          <div class="letter-tile tile-pending">
            <span class="tile-char">{l.char}</span>
            <span class="tile-name">{l.name}</span>
            <span class="tile-num">{l.num} of 22</span>
          </div>
        )
      ))}
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ══ ALEPH ══ -->
  <section class="hl-section study-section" id="aleph">
    <div class="letter-header">
      <div class="heb-char">א</div>
      <div class="letter-title-block">
        <div class="letter-number">Letter 1 of 22</div>
        <div class="letter-name-row">Aleph</div>
        <div class="letter-meanings">Strength &nbsp;·&nbsp; Leader &nbsp;·&nbsp; First</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <p class="bridge">"The letter Aleph speaks of the one who stands first and above all. Yahushua fulfills that in the most specific way — Yahuah appointed and ordained Him as firstborn, the first man through the door of resurrection and the first of an entirely new creation."</p>

    <div class="concept-line"><span>Concept —</span> First of the New Creation</div>
    <div class="section-rule"></div>

    <p class="connection">
      Yahushua is the firstborn of the new creation — the first man to be resurrected and glorified by the Father. His resurrection is not the end of the story, it is the beginning of an entirely new one. Every person who is born again enters that same new creation He opened. He holds the first rank not because of age or pre-existence, but because Yahuah appointed Him as the first through the door — the prototype of everything the Father is building. Just as the first Adam was the beginning of one creation, the Last Adam is the beginning of another.
    </p>

    <div class="verses">
      <div class="verse-block">
        <span class="verse-ref">Colossians 1:15</span>
        <span class="verse-text">"He is the image of the invisible Elohim, the firstborn over all creation."</span>
      </div>
      <div class="verse-block">
        <span class="verse-ref">Psalm 89:27</span>
        <span class="verse-text">"I will also appoint him my firstborn, the highest of the kings of the earth."</span>
      </div>
      <div class="verse-block">
        <span class="verse-ref">Revelation 3:14</span>
        <span class="verse-text">"These are the words of the Amen, the faithful and true witness, the beginning (firstborn/ruler) of the creation of Elohim." — Yahushua speaking about Himself.</span>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="study-note">
      <span class="note-label">Study Note — Psalm 89:27</span>
      <p class="note-text">The language Yahuah uses here is <strong>appointment</strong> — "I will appoint him my firstborn." Yahushua did not hold this title by nature — He was <strong>chosen and set apart for it</strong> before the world began, then He earned it by walking it out perfectly through death and resurrection. That makes the appointment far more remarkable: Yahuah ordained a man to be first, and that man delivered on it completely.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ══ MEM ══ -->
  <section class="hl-section study-section" id="mem">
    <div class="letter-header">
      <div class="heb-char">מ</div>
      <div class="letter-title-block">
        <div class="letter-number">Letter 13 of 22</div>
        <div class="letter-name-row">Mem</div>
        <div class="letter-meanings">Mighty &nbsp;·&nbsp; Revealed &nbsp;·&nbsp; Hidden</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <p class="bridge">"The letter Mem literally stands for water — it is the ancient picture of waves on the surface. Yahushua took that meaning and made it personal. He did not point to water or describe water — He claimed to be the source of it."</p>

    <div class="concept-line"><span>Concept —</span> Living Water</div>
    <div class="section-rule"></div>

    <p class="connection">
      No prophet, priest, or king in all of Scripture said what Yahushua said at Jacob's well. He identified Himself as the source of living water — water that ends thirst permanently, water that wells up into eternal life. He repeated it at the Feast of Tabernacles, standing in the Temple courts and crying out for anyone who thirsted to come to Him. No other man in Scripture ever made this claim about themselves. It belongs to Yahushua alone.
    </p>

    <div class="verses">
      <div class="verse-block">
        <span class="verse-ref">John 4:13–14</span>
        <span class="verse-text">"Whoever drinks of this water will thirst again, but whoever drinks of the water that I shall give him will never thirst. The water that I shall give him will become in him a fountain of water springing up into everlasting life."</span>
      </div>
      <div class="verse-block">
        <span class="verse-ref">John 7:37–38</span>
        <span class="verse-text">"If anyone thirsts, let him come to Me and drink. He who believes in Me, as the Scripture has said, out of his heart will flow rivers of living water."</span>
      </div>
      <div class="verse-block">
        <span class="verse-ref">Isaiah 12:3</span>
        <span class="verse-text">"Therefore with joy you will draw water from the wells of salvation." — Written 700 years before His birth.</span>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="study-note">
      <span class="note-label">Study Note — Isaiah 12:3</span>
      <p class="note-text">The Hebrew word translated <strong>"salvation"</strong> in this verse is <strong>יְשׁוּעָה — Yahushua</strong>. The verse literally reads: <em>"you will draw water from the wells of Yahushua."</em> Isaiah named Him by letter 700 years before He stood in the Temple courts and declared the same thing about Himself. This is not a coincidence of translation — it is His name embedded in the prophecy, tied directly to the image of water.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ══ TAV ══ -->
  <section class="hl-section study-section" id="tav">
    <div class="letter-header">
      <div class="heb-char">ת</div>
      <div class="letter-title-block">
        <div class="letter-number">Letter 22 of 22</div>
        <div class="letter-name-row">Tav</div>
        <div class="letter-meanings">Seal &nbsp;·&nbsp; Covenant &nbsp;·&nbsp; Complete</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <p class="bridge">"The letter Tav means seal, covenant, and complete — it is the final mark, the last word. Yahushua is every one of those things: He became the New Covenant in the flesh, He sealed it with His blood, and on the cross He declared it complete with the words 'It is finished.'"</p>

    <div class="concept-line"><span>Concept —</span> Last Adam — New Covenant</div>
    <div class="section-rule"></div>

    <p class="connection">
      The Tav is the last letter — the seal at the end. Yahushua is the Last Adam: where the first Adam brought death into creation through disobedience, the Last Adam brought life back through perfect obedience and sacrifice. At the last supper He took the cup and declared that His blood was the seal of a New Covenant. When He said "It is finished" on the cross, He was the final letter completing the word Yahuah had been writing since Genesis.
    </p>

    <div class="verses">
      <div class="verse-block">
        <span class="verse-ref">1 Corinthians 15:45</span>
        <span class="verse-text">"The first man Adam became a living being. The last Adam became a life-giving spirit."</span>
      </div>
      <div class="verse-block">
        <span class="verse-ref">Luke 22:20</span>
        <span class="verse-text">"This cup is the new covenant in My blood, which is shed for you." — His own words.</span>
      </div>
      <div class="verse-block">
        <span class="verse-ref">Isaiah 42:6</span>
        <span class="verse-text">"I will keep you and give you as a covenant for the people, as a light for the nations."</span>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="study-note">
      <span class="note-label">Study Note — Isaiah 42:6</span>
      <p class="note-text">This verse is Yahuah speaking directly to His Servant — the Messianic Servant of Isaiah 42–53, identified throughout as a specific person appointed for a specific mission. The phrase <strong>"give you as a covenant"</strong> means the Servant Himself becomes the covenant — He is not merely the messenger of it, He is the substance of it. This is fulfilled in Yahushua and confirmed in His own words in Luke 22:20 and 1 Corinthians 11:25.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ══ PLACEHOLDERS ══ -->
  <section class="hl-section">
    <h2 class="hl-section-title hl-center">Remaining Letters — In Study</h2>
    <p class="hl-section-sub hl-center">Each of these will receive the same depth of treatment. Studies are being written.</p>
    <div class="placeholder-grid">
      {allLetters.filter(l => !l.done).map((l) => (
        <div class="placeholder-card">
          <span class="ph-char">{l.char}</span>
          <span class="ph-name">{l.name}</span>
          <span class="ph-num">{l.num} of 22</span>
          <span class="ph-status">In Study</span>
        </div>
      ))}
    </div>
  </section>

</HebrewLayout>

<style>
  /* ── Hebrew display in hero ── */
  .heb-display {
    display: block;
    font-size: clamp(2.5rem, 6vw, 4rem);
    color: #C9A84C;
    direction: rtl;
    line-height: 1.1;
    margin: 1rem auto 1.5rem;
    opacity: 0.9;
  }

  /* ── Letter overview grid: 5 columns ── */
  .letter-grid {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(5, 1fr);
    gap: 0.6rem;
  }

  .letter-tile {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    align-items: center;
    gap: 0.2rem;
    padding: 0.75rem 0.5rem 0.6rem;
    border-radius: 4px;
    border: 1px solid #2e1f0d;
    text-decoration: none;
    transition: border-color 0.2s, background 0.2s;
  }

  .tile-done {
    background: rgba(201, 168, 76, 0.06);
    border-color: rgba(201, 168, 76, 0.25);
    cursor: pointer;
  }
  .tile-done:hover {
    background: rgba(201, 168, 76, 0.12);
    border-color: rgba(201, 168, 76, 0.5);
  }

  .tile-pending {
    background: rgba(255,255,255,0.015);
    opacity: 0.45;
    cursor: default;
  }

  .tile-char {
    font-size: 2rem;
    color: #C9A84C;
    line-height: 1;
    direction: rtl;
  }
  .tile-done .tile-char { color: #e8c97a; }

  .tile-name {
    font-family: 'Cinzel', serif;
    font-size: 0.65rem;
    letter-spacing: 0.1em;
    color: #c4ad84;
    text-transform: uppercase;
  }
  .tile-num {
    font-family: 'Cinzel', serif;
    font-size: 0.55rem;
    color: #5a3e1a;
    letter-spacing: 0.05em;
  }
  .tile-badge {
    font-family: 'Cinzel', serif;
    font-size: 0.5rem;
    letter-spacing: 0.15em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: #C9A84C;
    border: 1px solid rgba(201,168,76,0.3);
    border-radius: 2px;
    padding: 1px 5px;
    margin-top: 0.15rem;
  }

  /* ── Study section layout ── */
  .study-section {
    max-width: 820px !important;
  }

  .letter-header {
    display: flex;
    align-items: flex-start;
    gap: 1.75rem;
    margin-bottom: 0.75rem;
  }

  .heb-char {
    font-size: 80px;
    color: #C9A84C;
    line-height: 1;
    direction: rtl;
    min-width: 80px;
    text-align: center;
    opacity: 0.85;
    flex-shrink: 0;
  }

  .letter-title-block {
    padding-top: 8px;
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: 5px;
  }

  .letter-number {
    font-family: 'Cinzel', serif;
    font-size: 10px;
    letter-spacing: 0.25em;
    color: #5a4030;
    text-transform: uppercase;
  }

  .letter-name-row {
    font-family: 'Cinzel', serif;
    font-size: 26px;
    font-weight: 500;
    color: #f0e0bf;
    letter-spacing: 0.05em;
  }

  .letter-meanings {
    font-family: 'Cinzel', serif;
    font-size: 11px;
    color: #8B6914;
    letter-spacing: 0.15em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
  }

  .bridge {
    font-size: 1rem;
    color: #A89878;
    font-style: italic;
    line-height: 1.85;
    margin-bottom: 1rem;
    padding-left: calc(80px + 1.75rem);
  }

  .concept-line {
    font-family: 'Cinzel', serif;
    font-size: 11px;
    color: #C9A84C;
    letter-spacing: 0.14em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    padding-left: calc(80px + 1.75rem);
    margin-bottom: 1.5rem;
  }
  .concept-line span {
    color: #5a4030;
    margin-right: 8px;
  }

  .section-rule {
    width: 100%;
    height: 1px;
    background: rgba(201,168,76,0.15);
    margin-bottom: 1.5rem;
  }

  .connection {
    font-size: 1.05rem;
    color: #A89878;
    line-height: 1.9;
    margin-bottom: 2rem;
  }

  /* ── Verse block ── */
  .verses {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    border: 1px solid rgba(201,168,76,0.2);
    border-radius: 2px;
    overflow: hidden;
    margin-bottom: 1.5rem;
  }

  .verse-block {
    background: rgba(201,168,76,0.04);
    padding: 1rem 1.25rem;
    border-bottom: 1px solid rgba(201,168,76,0.12);
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: 4px;
  }
  .verse-block:last-child { border-bottom: none; }

  .verse-ref {
    font-family: 'Cinzel', serif;
    font-size: 10px;
    letter-spacing: 0.15em;
    color: #C9A84C;
    text-transform: uppercase;
  }

  .verse-text {
    font-size: 1rem;
    color: #e8e0cc;
    line-height: 1.75;
    font-style: italic;
  }

  /* ── Study note ── */
  .study-note {
    background: rgba(122,46,26,0.1);
    border-left: 2px solid rgba(122,46,26,0.45);
    padding: 1rem 1.25rem;
    border-radius: 0 2px 2px 0;
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: 0.4rem;
  }

  .note-label {
    font-family: 'Cinzel', serif;
    font-size: 9px;
    letter-spacing: 0.25em;
    color: #A0522D;
    text-transform: uppercase;
  }

  .note-text {
    font-size: 0.95rem;
    color: #A89878;
    line-height: 1.75;
    margin: 0;
  }
  .note-text strong { color: #e8e0cc; font-weight: 500; }
  .note-text em { color: #C9A84C; font-style: italic; }

  /* ── Placeholder grid ── */
  .placeholder-grid {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(5, 1fr);
    gap: 0.6rem;
  }

  .placeholder-card {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    align-items: center;
    gap: 0.2rem;
    padding: 1rem 0.5rem 0.75rem;
    border: 1px solid #1e1409;
    border-radius: 4px;
    opacity: 0.4;
  }

  .ph-char {
    font-size: 2rem;
    color: #C9A84C;
    line-height: 1;
    direction: rtl;
  }
  .ph-name {
    font-family: 'Cinzel', serif;
    font-size: 0.65rem;
    letter-spacing: 0.1em;
    color: #8a6028;
    text-transform: uppercase;
  }
  .ph-num {
    font-family: 'Cinzel', serif;
    font-size: 0.55rem;
    color: #4a3018;
  }
  .ph-status {
    font-family: 'Cinzel', serif;
    font-size: 0.5rem;
    letter-spacing: 0.15em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: #5a3e1a;
    margin-top: 0.15rem;
  }

  /* ── Responsive ── */
  @media (max-width: 760px) {
    .letter-grid,
    .placeholder-grid {
      grid-template-columns: repeat(4, 1fr);
    }
    .bridge,
    .concept-line {
      padding-left: 0;
    }
    .heb-char { font-size: 60px; min-width: 60px; }
    .letter-name-row { font-size: 20px; }
  }

  @media (max-width: 480px) {
    .letter-grid,
    .placeholder-grid {
      grid-template-columns: repeat(4, 1fr);
    }
    .letter-header { flex-direction: column; gap: 0.5rem; }
  }
</style>
